.TH "SOVEREIGN-OSCTL" "1" "2026-07-14" "sovereign-os 0.3.0" "sovereign-os Operator Manual"
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
sovereign-osctl - lifecycle management CLI for sovereign-os
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl\f[R] \f[I]command\f[R] [\f[I]subcommand\f[R]]
[\f[I]options\f[R]]
.PP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl\f[R] {\f[B]help\f[R] | \f[B]version\f[R]}
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl\f[R] is the single operator entry point for
inspecting, configuring, auditing, maintaining, and decommissioning an
installed sovereign-os system.
It operates both from a source checkout and from an installed library
tree.
.PP
The active OS profile is read from
\f[V]/etc/sovereign-os/active-profile\f[R] and falls back to
\f[V]sain-01\f[R].
Commands that mutate state retain their command-specific confirmation,
privilege, and dry-run gates.
\f[B]sovereign-osctl help\f[R] is a discovery summary, not an exhaustive
grammar; use the topic pages below and the command-specific help
implemented by delegated tools where available.
.SH PRIMARY COMMAND FAMILIES
.TP
\f[B]status\f[R] [\f[B]\[en]json\f[R]], \f[B]overview\f[R], \f[B]doctor\f[R]
Inspect system state and run profile-conditioned health checks.
.TP
\f[B]assistant\f[R], \f[B]init\f[R], \f[B]wizard\f[R], \f[B]next-steps\f[R]
Run onboarding, first-login, and guided operator flows.
.TP
\f[B]profiles\f[R], \f[B]whitelabel\f[R], \f[B]hooks\f[R], \f[B]env\f[R]
Inspect and customize profiles, branding, lifecycle hooks, and
\f[V]SOVEREIGN_OS_*\f[R] configuration.
.TP
\f[B]models\f[R], \f[B]model-serve\f[R], \f[B]inference\f[R], \f[B]gateway\f[R], \f[B]router\f[R]
Operate model catalogs, serving processes, inference tiers, the
provider-inversion gateway, and routing.
.TP
\f[B]frontend\f[R], \f[B]openclaw\f[R], \f[B]open-computer\f[R], \f[B]jobs\f[R], \f[B]plane\f[R]
Operate the desktop/agent layer, background jobs, and the sovereign
compute plane.
.TP
\f[B]trinity\f[R], \f[B]weaver\f[R], \f[B]auditor\f[R], \f[B]selfdef\f[R], \f[B]perimeter\f[R]
Inspect and manage Pulse, Weaver, Auditor, selfdef, and the Tetragon
security perimeter.
.TP
\f[B]audit\f[R], \f[B]diagnose\f[R], \f[B]health\f[R], \f[B]alerts\f[R], \f[B]journal\f[R], \f[B]history\f[R]
Run audit and diagnostic surfaces and inspect operational findings.
.TP
\f[B]maintenance\f[R], \f[B]snapshot\f[R], \f[B]config-snapshot\f[R], \f[B]config-restore\f[R]
Run recurrent maintenance and configuration recovery workflows.
.TP
\f[B]install image\f[R] [\f[B]\[en]plan\f[R]] \f[I]image\f[R] \f[B]\[en]to\f[R] \f[I]device\f[R]
Plan or write a built image.
The write path refuses the running root device and requires the explicit
destructive confirmation gate.
.TP
\f[B]decommission \[en]plan\f[R]
Preview every decommission phase without changing state.
.TP
\f[B]decommission start\f[R]
Begin the interactive, confirmation-gated decommission flow.
.PP
\f[B]doc-coverage\f[R], \f[B]surface-map\f[R],
\f[B]ux-design-audit\f[R], \f[B]anti-minimization-audit\f[R],
\f[B]architecture-qa\f[R], \f[B]coverage\f[R] : Inspect the
project\[cq]s governance and operator-surface contracts.
.SH MANUAL SUITE
.PP
The main page explains the lifecycle and safety model.
Detailed syntax, workflows, ownership, and examples are divided by
operator concern:
.TP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl-models\f[R](1)
Models, inference, routing, serving, evaluation, adaptation, and
science.
.TP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl-agents\f[R](1)
Frontends, agent runtimes, background jobs, compute-plane placement,
state fabric, sessions, approvals, and rollback.
.TP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl-hardware\f[R](1)
CPU, GPU, memory, storage, network, PCIe, thermals, power, and BIOS.
.TP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl-security\f[R](1)
Perimeter, selfdef, Secure Boot, authentication, permissions, hardening,
firewall, trust, and audit.
.TP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl-operations\f[R](1)
Status, diagnostics, observability, maintenance, recovery, and daily
use.
.TP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl-governance\f[R](1)
Architecture, doctrine, compliance, UX, documentation, and surface
audits.
.TP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl-install\f[R](1)
Bootstrap, profiles, initialization, customization, image installation,
configuration snapshots, and decommissioning.
